questionRound.0.question.11.answer: The game played out in such a way that the second-best offer was usually chosen by every participant  except in some cases for the first and last participants. For most of the game (before I noticed this trend) I simply used the first selection to predict the final selection  and from that I was able to predict all the selections.

The first player tries to maximize his earnings and starts by picking the box that has the greatest amount and then based on that amount  looks at the corresponding column of the last player and figures out which box the last player will choose. The first player for each of the remaining players until he reaches his own matrix again. If the second player would select a column that allows player 1 to have greatest of the 4 earnings  he will pick that row  otherwise he will pick the other row. I assumed that each player was rational and would follow this general pattern.

I worked back from the last  deciding which they would choose knowing what the second coordinate is (based on the first color's answer)  what they choose gives you the second coordinate on the second to last color and the first coordinate is found by whichever is more beneficial based on the second coordinate and so on. | If I was first  I would work out what every other color would find best to choose using the previous method  working back to the first color  and which ever result was better  I choose that coordinate.

I assumed that everyone would choose to pick the higher number and used the same strategy as me  so if I was first  I would look to see what the last person would pick if I chose X then decide what the second to last person would pick if they used the same strategy of working backwards from the last person to pick to the first. Then I would do the same with Y to find out what my options were based on the other people's answers. Then based on the end result of those two  I would pick the higher number of the two. If I wasn't first then I would see what the first person picked and assume what the last person would pick the higher number in that column  then do the same with the rest of the people in reverse order until I go to my box. From there I would choose the better number in that column.

The entire game could be determined based on what the last person will pick. The choice for the last person was always obvious  and from there you could determine what everyone would pick if they were thinking ahead and going for the greatest number of tokens.

Everything was based off the fact that you knew the most right-wards column was going to pick the highest payoff in the color they know was already selected by the most left-wards column. Therefore  if you knew what the the most right-wards color was going to pick  you could select the row perpendicular to that row that would give you the highest return. If you were starting the game  you picked the row with the highest number that would yield the highest number according to the knowledge that the other members of the game were playing off the fact that they were basing their selection on the most right-wards color.
Looked at the last person's to decide what they would pick and then that starts a chain reaction to decide which choice is best for each color before.

If I was anything but the first player I would look to see what the first playeyer picked. From that I would figure out what the last player would pick and keep working my way back to see what my answer was. If I was the first player I would pick either one and then go back and check what the last player and work my way until I got to the second player to see what they would most likely check and see if that gave me the highest amount of tokens. If it didnt then I would change my answer to the other option. Hopefully that makes sense. The whole game is not to get the highet point in your personal square but to see what the other person would put to get the highest points and from there see where you could get the higher of two points from any particular row. It wasnt until the third match that I realized how the game worked. Once I figured it out I was able to get the highest points possible. From every row I picked I could predict what number I was going to get. There was only one match that the person following me picked the wrong row causing me to get the lower of the two boxes. Hope that made sense.

I played backwards. I always go the payoff of the last box  and see what they would choose baed on the results from the first box  and then i got to the box second to the right  and third to the right  and so on.

I would look at the possibilities for the first role to choose and pick the highest option. I would then work the problem backwards  looking at what the last role would choose as a result of this first choice all the way back to the first color. If I found that the second color would pick an option that would give me the result of the highest option in the first color's boxes  then I would keep that color and working backwards would know what each color would choose. If the choice of the first color and second color did not match up to give the first color the best outcome  I would repeat the process with the second highest option. I used this method if I was the first color. If I was any color following the first color  the process was shorter as I had more information on what other colors had chosen. For example  if I was last  I would already know what the first color chose and would simply choose which outcome gave me the higher number of credits.

I used the strategy through which I could get the most money while keeping in mind what the leftmost person had chosen and according to that  the amount the rightmost person would get. From there on  going from right to left  I would choose the box that provided me with the highest amount of money.

People in this study don't pay attention to the logic of the study. They just choose the highest number and hope the person after them will help them out. That's because human nature causes us to be selfish and inconsiderate. I used the strategy of helping out the person that preceeded me and had to have faith in the person that followed me. I think you should specify in the introduction that selfishness will not help in this experiment
